{"id": 26871, "date": "1987-02-17T11:00:00", "date_gmt": "1987-02-17T19:00:00", "guid": {"rendered": "https://estreetshuffle.com/?p=26871"}, "modified": "2026-06-09T10:02:49", "modified_gmt": "2026-06-09T17:02:49", "slug": "matr-bruce-springsteen-arlo-guthrie-joe-ely-and-jimmy-lafave-oklahoma-hills", "status": "publish", "type": "post", "link": "https://estreetshuffle.com/index.php/1987/02/17/matr-bruce-springsteen-arlo-guthrie-joe-ely-and-jimmy-lafave-oklahoma-hills/", "title": {"rendered": "Oklahoma Hills"}, "content": {"rendered": "<p>As official state songs go, Oklahoma&#8217;s got it pretty good.</p>\n<p>My home state of Pennsylvania has a rather unremarkable anthem.</p>\n<div class=\"jetpack-video-wrapper\"><span class=\"embed-youtube\" style=\"text-align:center; display: block;\"><iframe loading=\"lazy\" class=\"youtube-player\" width=\"758\" height=\"427\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/WDiSCTlHl5Q?version=3&#038;rel=1&#038;showsearch=0&#038;showinfo=1&#038;iv_load_policy=1&#038;fs=1&#038;hl=en-US&#038;autohide=2&#038;wmode=transparent\" allowfullscreen=\"true\" style=\"border:0;\" sandbox=\"allow-scripts allow-same-origin allow-popups allow-presentation allow-popups-to-escape-sandbox\"></iframe></span></div>\n<p>New York&#8217;s official song is memorable&#8230; but perhaps just a bit dated.</p>\n<div class=\"jetpack-video-wrapper\"><span class=\"embed-youtube\" style=\"text-align:center; display: block;\"><iframe loading=\"lazy\" class=\"youtube-player\" width=\"758\" height=\"427\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/YgQqpHIts94?version=3&#038;rel=1&#038;showsearch=0&#038;showinfo=1&#038;iv_load_policy=1&#038;fs=1&#038;hl=en-US&#038;autohide=2&#038;wmode=transparent\" allowfullscreen=\"true\" style=\"border:0;\" sandbox=\"allow-scripts allow-same-origin allow-popups allow-presentation allow-popups-to-escape-sandbox\"></iframe></span></div>\n<p>New Jersey doesn&#8217;t even <em>have</em> a state song. (How is that still possible?)</p>\n<p>But Oklahoma has a great one:</p>\n<div class=\"jetpack-video-wrapper\"><span class=\"embed-youtube\" style=\"text-align:center; display: block;\"><iframe loading=\"lazy\" class=\"youtube-player\" width=\"758\" height=\"427\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/9sVBVOmx6Rk?version=3&#038;rel=1&#038;showsearch=0&#038;showinfo=1&#038;iv_load_policy=1&#038;fs=1&#038;hl=en-US&#038;autohide=2&#038;wmode=transparent\" allowfullscreen=\"true\" style=\"border:0;\" sandbox=\"allow-scripts allow-same-origin allow-popups allow-presentation allow-popups-to-escape-sandbox\"></iframe></span></div>\n<p>Woody Guthrie wrote &#8220;Oklahoma Hills,&#8221; but it was his cousin Jack who made it famous when the lesser-known Guthrie recorded a Western swing version and topped the charts with it for six weeks in 1945.</p>\n<p>More than a half-century later, Woody&#8217;s son performed &#8220;Oklahoma Hills&#8221; at a tribute concert for Woody, sponsored by the Rock and Roll Hall of Fame.</p>\n<p>Bruce Springsteen and Joe Ely joined Arlo for the performance, with each singer taking lead vocals for a verse&#8211;a one-time-only team-up that was thankfully captured on video.</p>\n<div class=\"jetpack-video-wrapper\"><span class=\"embed-youtube\" style=\"text-align:center; display: block;\"><iframe loading=\"lazy\" class=\"youtube-player\" width=\"758\" height=\"427\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/_56dNOn0mIw?version=3&#038;rel=1&#038;showsearch=0&#038;showinfo=1&#038;iv_load_policy=1&#038;fs=1&#038;hl=en-US&#038;autohide=2&#038;wmode=transparent\" allowfullscreen=\"true\" style=\"border:0;\" sandbox=\"allow-scripts allow-same-origin allow-popups allow-presentation allow-popups-to-escape-sandbox\"></iframe></span></div>\n<p>Jimmy LaFave was also there that night, but he didn&#8217;t take part in that particular song. Bruce rectified that almost a decade later, when he invited LaFave to join him on stage during the encore set of his solo acoustic show in Grand Prairie, Texas.</p>\n<div class=\"jetpack-video-wrapper\"><span class=\"embed-youtube\" style=\"text-align:center; display: block;\"><iframe loading=\"lazy\" class=\"youtube-player\" width=\"758\" height=\"427\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/aYt_65Anjtw?version=3&#038;rel=1&#038;showsearch=0&#038;showinfo=1&#038;iv_load_policy=1&#038;fs=1&#038;hl=en-US&#038;autohide=2&#038;wmode=transparent\" allowfullscreen=\"true\" style=\"border:0;\" sandbox=\"allow-scripts allow-same-origin allow-popups allow-presentation allow-popups-to-escape-sandbox\"></iframe></span></div>\n<p>Bruce and Jimmy&#8217;s performance of &#8220;Oklahoma Hills&#8221; was a brighter and stronger one than the Hall of Fame performance a decade earlier, with the two singers&#8217; guitars and voices blending nicely.</p>\n<p>Other than one other performance in 2006 (where Bruce was one of about 20 guitar players on stage), these are Bruce&#8217;s only two known performances of &#8220;Oklahoma Hills.&#8221;</p>\n<p><strong>Oklahoma Hills<br />\nFirst performed:</strong> September 29, 1996 (Cleveland, OH)<br />\n<strong>Last performed:</strong> January 15, 2006 (New York City, NY)</p>\n<p>\u00a9 May 17, 2021</p>\n", "protected": false}, "excerpt": {"rendered": "<p>At a 1996 Hall of Fame tribute concert, Bruce teamed up with Joe Ely and Arlo Guthrie for Woody Guthrie&#8217;s tribute to Oklahoma.</p>\n", "protected": false}, "author": 1, "featured_media": 69763, "comment_status": "open", "ping_status": "open", "sticky": false, "template": "", "format": "standard", "meta": {"_monsterinsights_skip_tracking": false, "_monsterinsights_sitenote_active": false, "_monsterinsights_sitenote_note": "", "_monsterinsights_sitenote_category": 0, "_jetpack_newsletter_access": "", "_jetpack_dont_email_post_to_subs": false, "_jetpack_newsletter_tier_id": 0, "_jetpack_memberships_contains_paywalled_content": false, "_jetpack_feature_clip_id": 0, "_jetpack_memberships_contains_paid_content": false, "footnotes": "", "jetpack_publicize_message": "", "jetpack